{{Infobox person | name = Gao Yu | image = Gao yu VOA.jpg | caption = Gao in August 2007 | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1944|2|23|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Chongqing]], [[Republic of China (1912–49)|Republic of China]] | alma_mater = [[Renmin University of China]] | occupation = {{Flatlist | * Journalist * columnist }} | known_for = }} {{Chinese name|[[Gao (surname)|Gao]]}}
'''Gao Yu''' ({{zh|s={{linktext|高瑜}}}}; born 23 February 1944)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nchrd.org/2014/12/prisoner-of-conscience-gao-yu/ |title=Gao Yu (高瑜) |date=2 December 2014 |website=[[Chinese Human Rights Defenders]] |access-date=27 September 2017}}</ref> is a Chinese [[journalist]] and [[dissident]] who has been repeatedly imprisoned.<ref name=IPI/>
==Early life== Gao was born in [[Chongqing]]. She attended the Language and Literature Department at the [[Renmin University of China]], where she majored in [[Literary theory|Literary Theory]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrohk.com.hk/index.php?cmd=detail&id=232859|title=爆機密拘高瑜|publisher=metrohk.com.hk|date=9 May 2014}}</ref>
==Career== Gao began her journalism career in 1979, as a reporter for the [[China News Service]].<ref name=IPI>Michael Kudlak, [http://www.freemedia.at/Heroes_IPIReport2.00/17Gao.htm IPI World Press Freedom Heroes: Gao Yu], ''IPI Report'', June 2000</ref> In 1988, she became deputy chief editor of ''Economics Weekly'', edited by dissident intellectuals.<ref name=IPI/> She also worked as a [[freelance journalist]] for different newspapers in [[China]] and in [[Hong Kong]]. In November 1988, she published an article in Hong Kong’s ''Mirror Monthly'', which was described by [[Beijing]]'s Mayor [[Chen Xitong]] as a "political program for turmoil and rebellion". He even branded her as a "people's enemy".<ref name=IPI/> She was arrested in 1989, after the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square protests]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Our Issues: Press Freedom {{!}} IWMF - Part 9532|url = http://www.iwmf.org/press/9532|website = www.iwmf.org|accessdate = 2015-11-26}}</ref> and released 15 months later because of health problems.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Document {{!}} Amnesty International|url = https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/ASA17/016/1999/en/|website = www.amnesty.org|accessdate = 2015-11-26}}</ref>
Gao was arrested again in October 1993, and in November 1994 was sentenced to six years, accused of having "published state secrets".<ref>{{Cite news|title = Chinese dissident gets medical parole|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/279946.stm|newspaper = BBC|date = 1999-02-15|access-date = 2015-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = China: "Leaking State Secrets": The Case of Gao Yu|url = https://www.hrw.org/summaries/s.china957.html|website = www.hrw.org|accessdate = 2015-11-26}}</ref> In February 1999, she was given parole in poor health.<ref>[http://asiapacific.amnesty.org/library/Index/ENGASA170161999?open&of=ENG-2S2 AI, 4 February 1999, Gao Yu: People's Republic of China]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = EST LIBÉRÉE POUR RAISONS MÉDICALES|url = http://www.ifex.org/1999/02/16/est_lib_r_e_pour_raisons_m_dicales/fr/|website = IFEX|accessdate = 2015-11-26}}</ref><ref>[https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/ASA17/016/1999/en/ "China: Update Medical Letter Writing Action: Gao Yu"]. Amnesty International, 5 March 1999</ref>
In 2014, Gao was arrested again a few weeks ahead of the 25th anniversary of the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|Tiananmen Square crackdown]]. The detention of the outspoken 70-year-old journalist was just one of several detentions of government critics over the previous days ahead of the politically sensitive 4 June anniversary.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Gao Yu arrested by Chinese authorities|url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/08/gao-yu-arrested-by-chinese-authorities|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-11-26|first = Associated Press in|last = Beijing}}</ref>
In April 2015, Beijing's high court convicted Gao of leaking state secrets and sentenced her to seven years in prison.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/17/world/asia/china-journalist-gao-yu-gets-7-year-sentence.html |title=Chinese Journalist Sentenced to 7 Years on Charges of Leaking State Secrets |date=16 April 2015 |newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> According to [[Reporters Without Borders]], the authorities accused Gao of sending "[[Document Number Nine]]" to a foreign news organization, although the document had already been posted online.<ref>[https://en.rsf.org/china-reporters-without-borders-reveals-17-04-2015,47785.html "Reporters Without Borders Reveals State Secrets In Reaction To Gao Yu’s Sentence"]. Reporters Without Borders, 17 April 2015</ref> Following an appeal, her sentence was reduced to five years on 26 November 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Imprisoned Chinese journalist's jail time reduced|url = http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/11/imprisoned-chinese-journalist-jail-time-reduced-151126054722547.html|website = www.aljazeera.com|accessdate = 2015-11-26}}</ref> Hours later, Chinese state media announced she has been released on medical parole, however the conviction for leaking state secrets was not overturned.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Jailed Chinese journalist Gao Yu released on medical parole|url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/26/jailed-chinese-journalist-gao-yu-sentence-cut-appeal|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 2015-11-27}}</ref> As of 2016, she is serving a five-year sentence under house arrest.<ref name="ej160401">{{cite news|title=Beijing police ransack dissident’s home after praise by Germany|url=http://www.ejinsight.com/20160401-beijing-police-ransack-dissidents-home-after-praise-by-germany/|work=Hong Kong Economic Journal|date=1 April 2016}}</ref>
German president [[Joachim Gauck]], on his first state visit to China in March 2016, raised the plight of Gao with the Chinese government.<ref name="nytimes160324">{{cite news|last1=Tatlow|first1=Didi Kirsten|title=German President Presses China on Political Prisoners During Visit|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/25/world/asia/china-germany-joachim-gauck.html?_r=0|work=The New York Times|date=24 March 2016}}</ref> Gao once wrote for the German broadcaster [[Deutsche Welle]].<ref name="nytimes160324"/> Days after Gauck's comments on Gao, Beijing municipal authorities and police raided her home, demolishing her study which they claimed was an illegal structure, and ransacking the rest of her home.<ref name="ej160401"/> Gao put up a fight but collapsed due to apparent high blood pressure.<ref name="ej160401"/> Gao stated that the raid was illegal and the authorities gave no advance notice.<ref name="ej160401"/> Sources claimed that the raid was conducted in retaliation for the German premier's comments.<ref name="ej160401"/> Gao's home has been ransacked by the police before, when they came to arrest her in 2014.<ref name="ej160401"/>
==Awards== While incarcerated, Gao Yu received the [[WAN-IFRA]] (World Association of Newspapers and News Publishers) [[Golden Pen of Freedom]] and the [[IWMF]] (International Women's Media Foundation) ''Courage in Journalism Award'' in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Press Freedom Resolution: Calling for the Release of Golden Pen Laureates and All Jailed Journalists - WAN-IFRA|url = http://www.wan-ifra.org/articles/2015/05/25/press-freedom-resolution-calling-for-the-release-of-golden-pen-laureates-and-all|website = www.wan-ifra.org|accessdate = 2015-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Courage in Journalism Awards: Awardees 1990-2015 {{!}} IWMF|url = http://www.iwmf.org/our-impact/courage-in-journalism-awards/award-winners/|website = www.iwmf.org|accessdate = 2015-11-27}}</ref> In March 1999, she became the first journalist to receive the [[UNESCO/Guillermo Cano World Press Freedom Prize]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = 1997 - Gao Yu, China: UNESCO-CI|url = http://portal.unesco.org/ci/en/ev.php-URL_ID=5709&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html|website = portal.unesco.org|accessdate = 2015-11-26}}</ref> In 2000 she was named one of [[International Press Institute]]'s 50 [[World Press Freedom Heroes]] of the 20th century.<ref name=IPI/>
