'''Jarmila Bělíková''' (April 27, 1948 &ndash; May 6, 2010)<ref name=vons>{{cite web |url=http://www.vons.cz/jarmila-belikova |title=Jarmila Bělíková |publisher=VONS}}</ref> was a [[Czechs|Czech]] psychologist, activist, and translator.<ref name="Associations1976">{{cite book|author=International Union of Food and Allied Workers' Associations|title=News Bulletin - International Union of Food & Allied Workers' Associations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j1ZZAAAAYAAJ|year=1976|publisher=International Union of Food & Allied Workers' Associations.|page=13}}</ref>
She was born in [[Brno]].<ref name=vons/> She studied medicine and during the 1970s worked in a treatment centre for female alcoholics. She then worked as a social worker specializing in the [[Romani people|Roma]] issue.<ref name=death/>
Bělíková was a signer of [[Charter 77]] and a founder of [[Committee for the Defense of the Unjustly Prosecuted|VONS]], the committee for the defence of the unjustly accused. In May 1979, she was arrested and imprisoned for seven months under the communist regime in Czechoslovakia. She returned to work as a psychologist in 1989.<ref name=death/>
During the 1980s, with [[Olga Havlová]], she established an association that published dissident books.<ref name=death/>
In 2001, she was awarded the Czech [[Medal of Merit (Czech Republic)|Medal of Merit]].<ref name=death/>
Bělíková died in [[Prague]]<ref name=vons/> at the age of 62.<ref name=death>{{cite news |url=http://www.radio.cz/fr/rubrique/faits/disparition-de-jarmila-belikova-ancienne-dissidente-et-fondatrice-du-vons |title=Disparition de Jarmila Bělíková, ancienne dissidente et fondatrice du VONS |publisher=Radio Praha |date=May 14, 2010}}{{fr icon}}</ref>
