{{Infobox scientist | name = Larned B. Asprey | image = File:Asprey60th small.jpg | caption = Larry and Marge Asprey with their family, celebrating their 60th wedding anniversary in 2004 | birth_date = {{Birth date|1919|3|19}} | birth_place = [[Sioux City, Iowa]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2005|3|6|1919|3|19}} | death_place = [[Mesilla Park, New Mexico]] | nationality = United States | work_institution = {{Plainlist| * [[Metallurgical Laboratory]] * [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] }} | alma_mater = {{Plainlist| * [[Iowa State University]] * [[University of California, Berkeley]] }} | doctoral_advisor = Burris B. Cunningham | thesis_title = Equilibria in the oxide systems of praseodymium and americium | thesis_year = 1949 | known_for = [[Actinide]], [[lanthanide]], [[rare-earth]] and [[fluorine]] chemistry | prizes = {{Plainlist| * Glenn T. Seaborg Actinide Separations Award (1986) }} | footnotes = }}
'''Larned (Larry) Brown Asprey''' (March 19, 1919 – March 6, 2005) was an American [[chemist]] noted for his work on [[actinide]], [[lanthanide]], [[rare-earth]], and [[fluorine]] chemistry, and for his contributions to nuclear chemistry on the [[Manhattan Project]] and later at the [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]].<ref> {{cite web | title = Dr. Larned "Larry" Brown Asprey | url = http://obits.abqjournal.com/obits/2005/03/11 | work = Obituaries | publisher = [[Albuquerque Journal]] | date = March 11, 2005 | accessdate = March 21, 2016 }}</ref>
==Biography== Asprey was born in [[Sioux City, Iowa]], on March 19, 1919, the son of Gladys Brown Asprey and Peter Asprey Jr. He had an older sister and a younger brother: [[mathematician]] and [[computer scientist]] [[Winifred Asprey]], founder of [[Vassar College]]'s computer science department,<ref> {{cite web | title = Winifred "Tim" Asprey, computer pioneer and longtime professor at Vassar College, dies at 90 | url = http://collegerelations.vassar.edu/2007/2497/ | publisher = Vassar Office of College Relations | accessdate = March 21, 2016 }}</ref> and military historian and writer [[Robert B. Asprey]].<ref> {{cite web | title = New College Receives Gift from Estate of Robert B. Asprey | url = http://www.ncf.edu/news/?p=1741 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100528115802/http://www.ncf.edu/news/?p=1741 | archivedate=May 28, 2010 | publisher = New College of Florida | date = June 15, 2009 }}</ref>
Asprey received a [[B.S.]] in [[chemical technology]] at [[Iowa State University]] in 1940, after which he took a job as an industrial chemist with the [[Campbell Soup Company]] in [[Chicago]]. He was drafted into the [[U.S. Army]] in 1941, and posted to [[Francis E. Warren Air Force Base|Fort Warren]], [[Wyoming]]. He applied for and was accepted into the [[Army Specialized Training Program]], which allowed soldiers to continue their education for a time, and went to [[Ohio State University]] to continue his chemistry studies. In January 1944, he was assigned to the [[Manhattan Project]]'s [[Special Engineer Detachment]],{{sfn|Asprey|2014|pp=105–106}} with the rank of [[technician third grade]].{{sfn|Asprey|2014|p=111}}
Asprey was posted to the [[Metallurgical Laboratory]] (Met Lab) at the [[University of Chicago]], where he joined the effort under [[Glenn T. Seaborg]] to devise techniques to separate and purify plutonium. There, with [[Herbert H. Anderson]], he developed the [[PUREX]] process (Plutonium–URanium EXtraction); their patent "Solvent Extraction Process for Plutonium" was filed in 1947.<ref name=eller> {{cite journal | url = http://arq.lanl.gov/source/orgs/nmt/nmtdo/AQarchive/05spring/05ARQspring.pdf | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140201164337/http://arq.lanl.gov/source/orgs/nmt/nmtdo/AQarchive/05spring/05ARQspring.pdf | archivedate = February 1, 2014 | title = Pioneer actinide chemist Larned Asprey dies | first = P. Gary | last = Eller |first2 = Bob |last2 = Penneman |first3 = Bob |last3 = Ryan | date = Spring 2005 | journal = The Actinide Research Quarterly | publisher = Los Alamos National Laboratory | pages = 13–17 | issn = 1936-3109 }}</ref> He was among the atomic-bomb scientists who signed the [[Szilárd petition]] in July 1945 to ask U.S. President [[Harry S. Truman]] to exercise extreme care in any decision to use the atomic bomb in the war.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dannen.com/decision/45-07-17.html | title = A Petition to the President of the United States |first=Gene |last=Dannen |website=dannen.com |accessdate=March 21, 2016 }}</ref>
In 1945, Asprey and [[Winston Manning]] measured the half-life of the synthetic isotope 95<sup>242</sup> at about 16 hours; the transient isotope was made by irradiating an early sample of the as-yet-unnamed relatively stable 95<sup>241</sup> with neutrons. The product after [[beta decay]] was yet another new element, 96<sup>242</sup>. These new unnamed elements created in the Met Lab in Chicago were announced to the world by [[Glenn Seaborg]] on November 11, 1945, on the radio show ''[[Quiz Kids]]''. Elements 95 and 96, originally called "pandemonium" and "delirium", were eventually named [[americium]] and [[curium]] by analogy with the chemically related elements [[europium]] and [[gadolinium]]. Asprey's later discovery, with [[S. E. Stephanou]] and [[Robert A. Penneman]] at Los Alamos, of the hexapositive, fluoride-soluble oxidation state of americium was one of the keys to the subsequent discovery of element 97, [[berkelium]], at [[Berkeley, California]], in 1949.<ref> {{Cite book | title = The Transuranium People: the Inside Story |author1=Darleane C. Hoffman |author2=Albert Ghiorso |author3=Glenn T. Seaborg | publisher = Imperial College Press | location = River Edge, New Jersey | year = 2000 | isbn = 978-1-86094-087-3 | pages = 114–136 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=4BtnthnFzy0C&pg=PA115&dq=asprey+half-life&cd=2#v=onepage&q=asprey%20half-life&f=false }}</ref>
While working in Chicago, he met his future wife Margaret (Marge) Williams, who also worked at the Metallurgical Laboratory.{{sfn|Asprey|2014|pp=101–105}} They were married at her parents' house in Chicago on May 3, 1944; the [[Catholic Church]] did not permit them to marry in a Church, because he was an atheist.{{sfn|Asprey|2014|pp=110, 349}} They eventually had seven children: Peter Larned, twins Elizabeth (Betty) and Barbara (Barb), Robert Russell (Bobby), Margaret Susan (Peggy), Thomas Arthur (Tom), and William John (Bill).{{sfn|Asprey|2014|pp=114, 133, 139, 154, 156}} Marge had seven sisters (including one who died in early childhood), and brother [[Grant R. Williams]] who died as a Navy test pilot.
Asprey was discharged from the Army in February 1946. He decided to enter the [[University of California, Berkeley]], and get his [[Ph.D.]] in chemistry under the supervision of Burris B. Cunningham, whom he had worked for at the Metallurgical Laboratory.{{sfn|Asprey|2014|p=120}} He wrote his thesis on "Equilibria in the oxide systems of praseodymium and americium",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oskicat.berkeley.edu/search~S53?/aAsprey/aasprey/1%2C1%2C2%2CB/frameset&FF=aasprey+larned+brown+1919&2%2C%2C2 |title=Equilibria in the oxide systems of praseodymium and americium |publisher=University of California, Berkeley |accessdate=March 21, 2016 }}</ref> They moved to [[Los Alamos, New Mexico]], in 1949, to work for the [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]], where he spent the rest of his career. He retired in 1986 after conducting more than thirty-five years of research on [[actinide]]s and [[lanthanide]]s and related chemistry. He published over 150 peer reviewed papers and held eight patents.<ref name=eller/> He was the third awardee of the [[American Chemical Society]]'s Glenn T. Seaborg Actinide Separations Award, in 1986.<ref> {{cite web | title = The Glenn T. Seaborg Actinide Separations Award | url = http://www.pnl.gov/main/publications/external/technical_reports/PNNL-SA-50126.pdf | work = 30th Actinide Separations Conference | page = 8 | publisher = Pacific Northwest National Laboratory | accessdate = December 13, 2009 }}</ref> His wife Marge also worked at Los Alamos, and was recognized for her work by the [[American Nuclear Society]] with the [[Walter H. Zinn Award]] in 2005,<ref> {{cite web | title = Walter H. Zinn Award recipients | url = http://www.ans.org/honors/recipients/va-zinn | work = Honors and Awards, Recipients | publisher = [[American Nuclear Society]] | accessdate = February 14, 2011 }}</ref> shortly after his death on March 6, 2005, in [[Mesilla Park, New Mexico]].<ref name=eller/> {{Clear}}
