{{Culture of Albania}}

The '''Traditions of Albania''' refers to the [[tradition]]s, [[belief]]s, [[value (ethics)|value]]s and [[Convention (norm)|custom]]s that belong within the [[Culture of Albania|culture]] of the [[Albanian people]]. Those traditions have influenced daily life in [[Albania]] for centuries and are still practiced throughout Albania, [[Balkans]] and [[Albanian diaspora|Diaspora]]. The Albanians have a unique culture, which progressed over the centuries of its strategic geography and its distinct historical evolution.

Albania is home to various [[Religion in Albania|religious communities]] such as [[Muslim]]s, [[Christian]]s and [[Jews]] and [[religious tolerance]] is among the most important values of the Albanian tradition. It is widely accepted, that Albanians are well known for those important values; the peaceful coexistence among the believers of different religions and beliefs in the country.<ref>{{cite web|author1=UNESCO|title=Island of Peace: Documentary on Religious Coexistence in Albania|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/member-states/single-view/news/island_of_peace_documentary_on_religious_coexistence_in_alb/|website=unesco.org|accessdate=22 July 2011|page=1|language=English}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=BBC|title=The country that's famous for tolerance|url=http://www.bbc.com/travel/story/20161024-the-worlds-most-tolerant-country|website=bbc.com|page=1|language=English}}</ref>

Albania is a hospitable culture; [[hospitality]] is a fundamental custom of the local society and [[Albanian cuisine|serving food]] is integral to the hosting of guests and visitors. It is not infrequent for visitors to be invited to eat and drink with locals. The medieval Albanian [[Kanun (Albania)|code of honor]], called [[Besa (Albanian culture)|Besa]], resulted to look after guests and strangers as an act of recognition and gratitude.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Mirjona SADIKU|title=Page 1 A Tradition of Honor, Hospitality and Blood Feuds:Exploring the Kanun Customary Law inContemporary Albania.|url=http://js.ugd.edu.mk/index.php/BSSR/article/download/861/833.|website=js.ugd.edu.mk|pages=11-14|language=English|format=PDF}}</ref> 

